<DOC><DOCNO> AP880619-0075 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-88 1819EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Guerrillas     06-19 0195</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Colombia-Guerrillas,0200</SECOND><HEAD>Colombian Guerrillas Attack Two Towns, Kill Eight</HEAD><DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist guerrillas on Sunday attackedtwo Colombian towns, killing at least eight people including fourpolicemen, state and local authorities reported.   Guerrillas stormed the town of Supia, 124 miles northwest of thecapital of Bogota, authorities in the state of Caldas reported.They said the attack was by rebels of the Popular Liberation Army,a Maoist organization.   ``More than 100 armed guerrillas, women and men, joined in theattack,'' a Caldas official said, speaking on condition ofanonymity. He said the guerrillas attacked two banks and the town'smain square where peasants were attending a local fair.   ``They killed four policemen, one bank employee and a campesino(peasant)'' in the one-hour raid and then fled, the official said.He did not provide further details.   Guerrillas from the rebel group M-19 attacked the town of Silviain the state of Cauca, 186 miles south of the capital, according tolocal authorities. They said the gunmen robbed a farmerscooperative and then left taking two rsidents as hostages.   The captives were slain outside the town, said a spokesman forthe army's Third Brigade.</TEXT></DOC>